    <stitle>STEERING COLUMN ASSEMBLY, TILT/TELESCOPING - ASSEMBLE</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>ASSEMBLE</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="assemble" graphiccount="3">
            <title>UNIVERSAL JOINTS</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Make certain parts are clean before assembly.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Rest yoke on hard surface. Tap one bearing part way into yoke with a soft hammer (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500909">Figure 9</hotlnk>). Be certain bearings are started straight in yoke.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0500909" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500909" filename="../figg05/G0500909.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 9. Install Bearing Part Way Into Yoke</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. YOKE</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. BEARING</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Insert spider through the opposite hole, without bearing, swinging it into place and
                    down into the partially installed bearing.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Turn assembly over and tap the opposite bearing part way into the yoke. Be certain to
                    start bearing straight in yoke.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Place yoke in vise with bearings against jaws of vise. Tighten vise slowly and the
                    bearings will be pressed into the yoke (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500910">Figure 10</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0500910" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500910" filename="../figg05/G0500910.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 10. Press Bearings Into Yoke</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. YOKE</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. SPIDER</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. YOKE</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. BEARING</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After pressing bearing into yoke, the spider may be off center in yoke. This is
                    desirable because it permits installation of snap ring on the side with the most clearance. Install
                    snap ring (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500911">Figure 11</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0500911" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500911" filename="../figg05/G0500911.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 11. Snap Ring Installation</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. GREASE FITTING</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. SNAP RING</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. YOKE</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After the first snap ring is in place, turn assembly over. The bearing with snap ring
                    installed should be on the bottom. Rest yoke on vise and strike bearing which is on top. This will
                    seat both bearings. Snap rings should rest against inside milled surface of yoke. Install remaining
                    snap ring.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Lubricate universal joint with Fleetrite EP2 Moly grease or equivalent NLGI #2
                    multi-purpose lithium grease.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After bearings are installed and lubricated, they must move freely. If tight, tap yoke
                    until free.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
